d₁↔d₃, d₂↔d₃, diagonal), acting on the 3D color subspace in each
chirality sector.

SU(2): 3 Pauli generators from triv↔hub rotations in the singlet
sector.

U(1)_Y: Hypercharge Y = (1/3)P_color + (−1)P_singlet.

**3.2 The Chirality Asymmetry**

                      Chirality behavior     Physical meaning
  SU(3) color         Preserves γ_F          Confining, vector-like
  SU(2) weak          Violates γ_F           Chiral, parity-violating

Root cause: Hub vertex (v=7) lives entirely in V₋ = {4,5,6,7}. The
trivial Z₇ rep spans BOTH V₊ and V₋ (0.571 dimensions in V₊, 0.429 in
V₋). Therefore the SU(2) generators τ = |triv⟩⟨hub| + h.c. necessarily
map V₊ ↔ V₋. No SU(2) generator can be chirality-preserving.

This is the geometric origin of electroweak parity violation: SU(2)_L
distinguishes chiralities because the singlet sector straddles the
vertex grading boundary. The W boson's inner fluctuation [D_F, τ_a] IS
the chirality-violating connection.

